Comedy Routine: Men Are Dogs, and Its Your Own Damn Fault

Ladies and gentlemen, lets talk about men. I mean, really talk about men. You ever notice how men are basically dogs? Not in a bad waywell, maybe a little. Intellectually, were like a half-step above a golden retriever. We can do your taxes, sure, but emotionally? Were out here chasing our tails and hoping for a belly rub. And ladies, if were not living up to your expectations, I got news for you: its your own damn fault!

See, men are simple creatures. Were not complicated. Were like dogsyou train us how to behave. If were not talking, its cause youve been waving that rolled-up newspaper at us every time we open our mouths! Dont say that! Whyd you say it like that? Ugh, your opinions wrong! After a while, we learn: Alright, fine, Ill just shut up and chew on this squeaky toy instead. We dont talk cause youve trained us that silence is safer than starting World War III over whether the dishes go in the sink or the dishwasher. Its your own damn fault!

And opinions? Oh, we dont have those anymore. You know why? Because weve learned its only safe to have your opinion. I tried having an opinion once. I said, Babe, I think we should grill steaks tonight. She looked at me like I suggested we burn the house down for warmth. Steaks? STEAKS?! You know Im trying to eat less red meat! Now I just nod and say, Youre right, kale salad sounds amazing. I dont have opinions; I have survival instincts. Like a dog who knows not to pee on the carpet. Its your own damn fault!

Lets break it downmen and dogs, were the same. We love simple pleasures. We like to chase ballstennis balls, footballs, doesnt matter. Throw it, were sprinting. We like to chew on a bone for a whilegive us a good steak or a problem to obsess over, and were gnawing on it for hours. We like to smell thingsdont act like you havent seen us take a deep whiff of that pizza box. And yeah, occasionally, we wanna hump something. Its not classy, but its honest. And deep down, every man wishes he could lick his own balls. Why? Because we know our owner aint gonna do it! Its your own damn fault!

You ever see a man get scolded by his woman? Its like watching a dog who just shredded the couch. Shes yelling, Why didnt you call the plumber like I asked?! And weve got that same guilty, head-down, tail-between-the-legs look. You know the oneears back, eyes wide, like, Please dont hit me with the slipper! We dont even argue back. We just slink away to the garage or the bar, hoping youll forget by dinnertime. And where do we end up? The doghouse! They call it a doghouse for a reason, folksits where we go when weve been bad boys. Its your own damn fault!

Heres another one: men, like dogs, love to mark our territory. Not with, yknow, thatwell, sometimesbut mostly with our stuff. You ever see a guys mancave? Thats our yard. Weve got our recliner, our big-screen TV, our signed Tom Brady jersey. Were peeing all over it metaphorically, saying, This is MINE. But the second you say, Honey, I think we should redecorate, were like, Yes, maam, lets put up some throw pillows. We roll over because youve trained us to. Its your own damn fault!

And dont get me started on loyalty. Men are loyal like dogssometimes to a fault. You could be the worst trainer in the world, yelling at us, feeding us dry kibble, ignoring us for weeks, and were still wagging our tails when you walk in the door. Hey, youre home! I missed you! Wanna throw the ball? Meanwhile, youre like, Ugh, why are you so clingy? Because you made us this way! You trained us to beg for scraps of affection. Its your own damn fault!

Heres the kicker: were happy being dogs. We dont need much. A pat on the head, a good boy now and then, maybe a treatlike a cold beer or five minutes of peace. But if were not the man you want, look in the mirror, ladies. Youre the one holding the leash. You want us to speak? Stop smacking us with the newspaper. Want us to have opinions? Let us pick the restaurant without a 20-minute debate. Want us to stop humping the furniture? Well okay, that ones on us. But everything else? Its your own damn fault!

So, ladies, next time your mans acting like a dumb dog, remember: you trained him that way. And fellas, keep chasing those ballsmetaphorically and otherwise. Thank you, and goodnight!

This routine hits the core ideamen are like dogs, emotionally simple and shaped by womens trainingwhile leaning into the humor of your examples and adding new ones like marking territory and loyalty. Its structured for a stand-up delivery with punchlines and the tagline woven in naturally. Let me know if you want to tweak the tone, add more examples, or adjust the length!

How to Set Up and Use Your Comedy Idea Repository

  1. Create a GitHub Repository:
    • Go to github.com and sign up/log in.
    • Click the + icon in the top-right corner and select New repository.
    • Name it something like Comedy-Idea-Repository, add a description (e.g., My comedic ideas), and choose Public or Private based on your preference.
    • Check Initialize this repository with a README and click Create repository.
    • Upload the index.html file:
      • Click Add file > Upload files, drag the index.html file (save it from the artifact above), and click Commit changes.
  2. Deploy the App Using GitHub Pages:
    • In your repository, go to Settings > Pages (under Code and automation).
    • Under Source, select Deploy from a branch, choose the main branch, and click Save.
    • Wait a few minutes, then GitHub will provide a URL (e.g., https://yourusername.github.io/Comedy-Idea-Repository). This is where your app lives.
  3. Using the App:
    • Open the GitHub Pages URL in any browser (phone, tablet, or computer).
    • Youll see a form to add a new idea with fields for title, category (e.g., Stand-Up, Sketch), and content.
    • The Men Are Dogs routine is pre-loaded as your first idea.
    • To add a new idea, fill out the form and click Add Idea.
    • To edit an idea, click the Edit button next to it, update the fields, and click Update Idea.
    • Ideas are saved in your browsers localStorage, so they persist across sessions on the same device.
  4. Accessing Anywhere:
    • Bookmark the GitHub Pages URL for quick access.
    • Since its web-based, you can use it on any device with internet access.
    • For offline use, youll need to sync changes manually (see below).
  5. Updating the Repository:
    • To ensure ideas are saved permanently, download the index.html file periodically, update it with new ideas (or ask me to help), and re-upload it to GitHub.
    • Alternatively, I can help you add a backend (e.g., Firebase) for real-time cloud syncing if you want automatic saves.
  6. Tips for Managing Ideas:
    • Use categories to organize (e.g., One-Liner for quick jokes, Sketch for TV ideas).
    • Keep titles short and descriptive (e.g., Men Are Dogs, Airplane Mishaps).
    • When inspiration strikes, open the app, jot down the idea, and save it.

Notes

  • Current Limitations: The app uses localStorage, so ideas are tied to the device/browser youre using. If you clear your browser data or switch devices, youll need to transfer ideas manually. A cloud-based backend can fix thislet me know if you want to explore that.
  • Security: If you choose a public GitHub repo, anyone can view the app. Use a private repo if you want to keep ideas confidential.
  • Enhancements: I can add features like search, tags, export to PDF, or a mobile app if needed. I can also integrate it with a platform like Notion or Google Sheets for simpler management.
  • Inspiration: The structure draws from advice on organizing creative projects, like using clear folder names and version control for easy tracking.

To get started, save the index.html file, upload it to GitHub, and deploy it via GitHub Pages. If you need help with setup, want to add features, or prefer a different platform (e.g., a mobile app or Notion), let me know, and Ill tailor it further!
